    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph TextIndent="16" Margin="0,0,0,0" TextAlignment="Justify" FontFamily="times new roman" FontSize="14">
      <Run Tag="__21">We see that Ichiro had a higher batting average than Nomar, but because he hit many more doubles, triples, and home runs, Nomar had a much higher slugging percentage. Ichiro walked a few more times than Nomar did. So which player had a better hitting year?</Run>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph TextIndent="16" Margin="0,0,0,0" TextAlignment="Justify" FontFamily="times new roman" FontSize="14">
      <Run Tag="__21">When a batter is hitting, he can cause good things (like hits or walks) to happen or cause bad things (outs) to happen. To compare hitters we must develop a metric that measures how the relative frequency of a batter&#x2019;s good events and bad events influence the number of runs the team scores.</Run>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph TextIndent="16" Margin="0,0,0,0" TextAlignment="Justify" FontFamily="times new roman" FontSize="14">
      <Run Tag="__21">In 1979 Bill James developed the first version of his famous Runs Created Formula in an attempt to compute the number of runs &#x201C;created&#x201D; by a hitter during the course of a season. The most easily obtained data we have available to determine how batting events influence Runs Scored are season-long team batting statistics. A sample of this data is shown in </Run>
